        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Band: We wish to obtain a sub-mm image of the microquasar SS433 shown in Figure 1 at radio wavelengths, but with slightly finer
resolution than 0.35′′ as shown. The choice of band 6, in the extended configuration would give us just this: images with 0.19′′ resolution.

Spectral configuration: Because we require polarisation observations we will use TDM mode. This would give us four spectral windows of 2 GHz bandwidth near 230 GHz. The maximum frequency span of 10 GHz between the extremes of the frequency range allows us to determine spectral indices accurately within the band.

Polarization: The maximum extent of SS433 over which we expect to detect polarized signal in Band 6 is ±2 arcsec from launch point, which is &lt;FWHM/3 for the 12m antennas, satisfying the requirement for accurate D-term calibration.

Sensitivity: We request 9.8 hours, including overheads, to give an on-source time of 6.2 hours which is necessary to reach the 1σ sensitivity level of 6.5 microJy/beam that will image the jets with ALMA to the same extent they are detected in the radio (in Fig. 2) assuming the radio spectral index continues. This duration will give good sampling of the UV-plane which will faciliate accurate deconvolution of the complex structures within the SS433 brightness distribution. This time is also necessary to achieve a sensitivity out to two complete spatial precession cycles based on extrapolating the known radio spectrum.

Scheduling: we request that these ALMA observations be scheduled between 6th February and May 11th 2015 in order that we may obtain “fairly simultaneous” supporting VLA observations. We understand that the dynamic scheduling of the VLA means that there is flexibility on that side. Note that actual simultaneity isn’t required; we can work with the ALMA and VLA observations being scheduled within a week or two of one another since we have now built up considerable experience of extracting data along the jet trace from an image at one epoch to “re-launch” the trace at a different epoch.</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
